@@eThe Cleric Tradition@@N

@@yThe Solar Court Priesthood@@N
The cleric tradition's origin lies in the Solar Court of the Undivided Disk, the
religious-administrative apparatus established to contain the Black Sun Shard and
legitimize the unification of the desert city-shrines. The Court organized its
priesthood into five offices: Dawn Liturgists who maintained cosmological calendars,
Ledger Priests who managed tribute and water-rights, Embalmer Houses who contained
the restless dead, the Jackal Tribunal who adjudicated posthumous accounts, and the
Seal College whose reverse-solar geometry kept the Shard dormant. Modern clerics
inherit most directly from the Dawn Liturgists and the Seal College.

@@yThe Great Shard Doctrine@@N
What distinguishes clerics from all other religious practices is the Shard Doctrine:
the understanding that the world contains an active metaphysical threat requiring
continuous institutional attention. Documented effects of the Shard include crops
failing under clear skies, the dead rising with false memories, households
forgetting their bloodlines, and water turning brackish without cause. Clerics
understand faith as infrastructure, not belief. Rites are maintenance procedures
that keep cosmic machinery functioning, not performances that express devotion.

@@yThe Diaspora@@N
When the Ninth Meridian Rite failed, the Solar Court was progressively isolated.
Surviving covenant-keepers traveled westward carrying what they could of the Court's
technical knowledge. Their arrival in the crossroads cities was not uniformly
welcome. Desert priests carrying texts about a cosmic threat buried under a pyramid
most people had never seen were not the most immediately useful resource.

@@yThe Inner and Outer Tradition@@N
Under the Violet Compact's registry law, clerics gained formal civic standing but
had to document their practices transparently. Certain elements of Solar Court
technical knowledge were kept from public registries. This created the inner and
outer tradition that persists today: the outer tradition is publicly accessible,
while the inner tradition maintains the technical Solar Court inheritance,
transmitted only within lineages of demonstrated commitment. A new cleric entering
through a crossroads city shrine may never know the inner tradition exists.
